Based on my understanding of the issue, I need to analyze the problem in the `TokeniserState` file more carefully. The test failure is related to parsing script tags with comments containing quotes. Looking at the failing test:

```java
@Test public void handlesQuotesInCommentsInScripts() {
    String html = "<script>\n" +
            "  <!--\n" +
            "    document.write('</scr' + 'ipt>');\n" +
            "  // -->\n" +
            "</script>";
    Document node = Jsoup.parseBodyFragment(html);
    assertEquals("<script>\n" +
            "  <!--\n" +
            "    document.write('</scr' + 'ipt>');\n" +
            "  // -->\n" +
            "</script>", node.body().html());
}
```

The issue is likely in the script parsing logic. Looking more closely at the script-related states in the TokeniserState file, I see the issue might be in how the state machine handles the script content after encountering certain characters.

Let me search for issues in the script-related states, particularly around the `ScriptDataDoubleEscapeEnd` and `ScriptDataEscaped` states:

Looking at the code, I notice that in the `ScriptDataDoubleEscapeEnd` state, there is this logic:

```java
void read(Tokeniser t, CharacterReader r) {
    if (r.matchesLetter()) {
        String name = r.consumeLetterSequence();
        t.dataBuffer.append(name.toLowerCase());
        t.emit(name);
        return;
    }

    char c = r.consume();
    switch (c) {
        case '\t':
        case '\n':
        case '\f':
        case ' ':
        case '/':
        case '>':
            if (t.dataBuffer.toString().equals("script"))
                t.transition(ScriptDataEscaped);
            else
                t.transition(ScriptDataDoubleEscaped);
            t.emit(c);
            break;
        default:
            r.unconsume();
            t.transition(ScriptDataDoubleEscaped);
    }
}
```

